The Hidden Gem Score seems to have weak association with the languages (either category or number) used in the film.

Based on languages that has been used in a large proportion among all Movies, the average Hidden Gem Scores of movies are greater than or equal to 5.0 are associated with Cantonese, French, German, Japanese, Japanese and English, Korean, Portuguese, Spanish; the average Hidden Gem Scores of movies are less than or equal to 5.0 are associated with English, English and French, English and German, English and Russian, English and Spanish, Hindi.

The graph for counts of language shows the association between Hidden Gem Score and number of languages. The number of languages here means how many languages are included for one movie. For instance, the Snowroller movie has Swedish, English, German,Norwegian. Thus, it counts four for the num of languages. The intention here is to see if more or less language versions of movies will affect the Hidden Gem Score.

From the graph, the mean score of only one kind of language is a bit higher than the others, but it does not exceed score 5. Also, the boxplot for movies with only one language shows wider ranges of scores from score 3-8.

And counts of languages from 2-7 have almost the same mean score with few fluctuations.

In conclusion, it is not easy to see there is an association between Hidden Gem Score and quantities of languages.

The Hidden Gem Score seems to have strong association with the Runtime Category of the film. Movies which are less than 60 minutes have a higher average Hidden Gem Score, around 7.5-8. People especially score higher for movies with 30-60 minutes.Movies which are 1-2 hours or larger than 2 hours only get around 4 Hidden Gem Score. Thus, the boxplot shows a significant relationship between Runtime Category and the Hidden Gem Score.

For runtime less than 30 minutes and 30-60 minutes, the Hidden Gem Scores are concentrated on 8.5 or higher. Even though the maximum counts for these two runtime categories are 25 and 50, the high value of Hidden Gem Scores are distinct compared to others. In general, the Runtime under 1 hour vs.Hidden Gem Scores graphs perform a normal distribution.

However, for runtime between 1-2 hour and longer than 2 hours, the Hidden Gem Scores are polarised they are concentrated on both scores lower than 4.0 and that higher than 8.0. Since the maximum counts for these two runtime categories are 200 and 500, it implies that there are more movies with runtime longer than 1 hour. In general, the Runtime under 1 hour vs.Hidden Gem Scores graphs perform a bimodal distribution.

Therefore, the companys theory that people are becoming more accepting of longer movies because they can watch them at home on Netflix and other content-collecting sites is not applicable to most people it is over-generalised.

Task 2: Factors of the Hidden Gem Score

# drop all the NA values
FlixGem_task2 = FlixGem  %>% drop_na(`Hidden Gem Score`)%>% drop_na(Languages) %>% drop_na(Runtime) %>% drop_na(`IMDb Score`) %>% drop_na(`Rotten Tomatoes Score`)  %>% drop_na(`Metacritic Score`) %>% select(`Hidden Gem Score`,Runtime,Languages,`IMDb Score`,`Rotten Tomatoes Score`,`Metacritic Score`,Title) 

# split Languages to get the number of languages for each movie
s <- strsplit(FlixGem_task2$Languages, split = ",")
#rebuild the table 
Language_table3 = data.frame(Title= rep(FlixGem_task2$Title,sapply(s, length)),
                             Runtime= rep(FlixGem_task2$Runtime, sapply(s, length)),
                            `Hidden Gem Score` = rep(FlixGem_task2$`Hidden Gem Score`, sapply(s, length)), 
                            Languages = unlist(s),
                            `Rotten Tomatoes Score` = rep(FlixGem_task2$`Rotten Tomatoes Score`, sapply(s, length)),
                            `Metacritic Score` = rep(FlixGem_task2$`Metacritic Score`, sapply(s, length)),
                            `IMDb Score` = rep(FlixGem_task2$`IMDb Score`, sapply(s, length))
                            )

Language_table3 = Language_table3 %>% group_by(Title,Hidden.Gem.Score) %>% mutate(num_of_language = n())

# select columns
Language_table3  = Language_table3[,c("Hidden.Gem.Score","Runtime","IMDb.Score","Rotten.Tomatoes.Score","Metacritic.Score","num_of_language")] 

 
# factor the Runtime 
Language_table3$Runtime = factor(Language_table3$Runtime)

# labeling
`Hidden Gem Score` = Language_table3$Hidden.Gem.Score
Runtime = Language_table3$Runtime
`IMDb Score` = Language_table3$IMDb.Score
`Rotten Tomatoes Score` = Language_table3$Rotten.Tomatoes.Score
`Metacritic Score` = Language_table3$Metacritic.Score
`num of language` = Language_table3$num_of_language

# regression tree
a = rpart(formula = `Hidden.Gem.Score` ~ Runtime + `IMDb Score` + `Rotten Tomatoes Score` + `Metacritic Score` + `num of language`,
          data = Language_table3, method = "anova",
         control = list(minsplit = 11, maxdepth = 8, cp = 0.003))

rpart.plot(a)

From what we get in the regression tree, we easily see that the rotten tomato score accounts for a large proportion and the root of the tree is also rotten tomato scores. Thus, we conclude the Rotten Tomato Score is the most important feature to predict the hidden Gem Score.

The other categories like Metacritic Score ,IMDb Score and Runtime do show importance in the regression tree, but not as significant as the Rotten Tomato Score.

The number of languages has least significance on Hidden Gem Score.

In Task 1, we get the correlation between Rotten Tomato Score and Hidden Gem Score is the largest among three different scores. And in task 2, we can also get this conclusion. Also, compared to task 1, we can prove that the number of languages are not significantly correlated to Hidden Gem Score and Metacritic Score ,IMDb Score and Runtime show weak associations.

Task 3: An H-index for directors

FlixGem_task3 <- FlixGem  %>% drop_na(`Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na(Director)
FlixGem_task3_count <- FlixGem_task3 %>% group_by(Director) %>% mutate(film_num = n()) %>% mutate(HG_H = NA)

# initialize the indices
counter = 1
idx = 1

# fill HG-H index in the tibble
for (i in FlixGem_task3_count$Director){
  score <- filter(FlixGem_task3_count, Director==i)$`Hidden Gem Score`
  while (counter <= FlixGem_task3_count$film_num[idx]){
    accumu = 0
    for (s in score){
      if(counter <= s){
        accumu = accumu + 1
      }
    }
    if (accumu >= counter){
        FlixGem_task3_count$HG_H[idx] = counter
    }
    counter = counter + 1
  }
  idx = idx + 1
  counter = 1
}

# the top 10 directors according to an Hidden Gem H-index
FlixGem_task3_count_unique <- FlixGem_task3_count[,c("Director", "HG_H")] %>% unique() %>% arrange(desc(HG_H))
FlixGem_task3_count_unique[1:10,]
